    {
      "content": "Configuring a custom domain name for an Azure website",
      "pos": [
        1,
        54
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you create a website, Azure provides a friendly subdomain on the azurewebsites.net domain so your users can access your website using a URL like http://&amp;lt;mysite&gt;.azurewebsites.net.",
      "pos": [
        56,
        243
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, if you configure your websites for Shared or Standard mode, you can map your website to your own domain name.",
      "pos": [
        244,
        362
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Optionally, you can use Azure Traffic Manager to load balance incoming traffic to your website.",
      "pos": [
        364,
        459
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information on how Traffic Manager works with Websites, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Controlling Azure Web Sites Traffic with Azure Traffic Manager<ept id=\"p1\">][trafficmanager]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        460,
        610
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        614,
        798
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The procedures in this task apply to Azure Websites; for Cloud Services, see <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;a href=\"/develop/net/common-tasks/custom-dns/\"&gt;</ph>Configuring a Custom Domain Name in Azure<ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>."
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The steps in this task require you to configure your websites for Shared or Standard mode, which may change how much you are billed for your subscription.",
      "pos": [
        802,
        969
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a href=\"/pricing/details/web-sites/\"&gt;</ph>Websites Pricing Details<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph> for more information.",
      "pos": [
        970,
        1062
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this article:",
      "pos": [
        1064,
        1080
      ]
    },
    {
